{
  "Why is genetic diversity important for a population's long-term survival?": "",
  "It guarantees that no individuals will ever die from disease": "",
  "It makes all individuals look the same": "",
  "It eliminates the need for reproduction": "",
  "It provides the variation needed for populations to adapt to changing environmental conditions": "",
  "Genetic diversity provides the raw material for natural selection. Populations with greater genetic variation are more likely to contain individuals that can survive environmental changes, diseases, or new stresses.": "",
  "What is inbreeding depression?": "",
  "A type of habitat destruction": "",
  "The migration of individuals between populations": "",
  "A reduction in fitness and health caused by mating between closely related individuals, exposing harmful recessive alleles": "",
  "An increase in fitness due to mating between related individuals": "",
  "Inbreeding depression occurs when related individuals mate, increasing homozygosity and the expression of harmful recessive alleles, leading to reduced survival, fertility, and overall fitness.": "",
  "What is genetic drift?": "",
  "The movement of organisms from one area to another": "",
  "Random changes in allele frequencies that are most significant in small populations": "",
  "A consistent directional change in allele frequencies due to natural selection": "",
  "The gradual increase in genetic diversity over time": "",
  "Genetic drift is the random fluctuation of allele frequencies due to chance events in reproduction. Its effects are strongest in small populations, where it can lead to the loss of alleles and reduced genetic diversity.": "",
  "How does gene flow between populations affect genetic diversity?": "",
  "It causes all populations to go extinct": "",
  "It always decreases genetic diversity": "",
  "It has no effect on genetic diversity": "",
  "It introduces new alleles, increasing genetic diversity within populations": "",
  "Gene flow (migration of individuals between populations) introduces new alleles, increasing genetic diversity within receiving populations and reducing genetic differences between populations.": "",
  "Which situation would most likely lead to a loss of genetic diversity?": "",
  "A population experiencing high mutation rates": "",
  "A large population with high immigration rates": "",
  "A population in a stable, resource-rich environment": "",
  "A small, isolated population with no gene flow from other populations": "",
  "Small, isolated populations lose genetic diversity through genetic drift and inbreeding because there is no influx of new alleles from other populations, and random events disproportionately affect allele frequencies.": "",
  "What is the founder effect?": "",
  "When a large population splits into two equal halves": "",
  "When natural selection favors the strongest individuals": "",
  "When the first species to colonize an area determines succession": "",
  "When a small group colonizes a new area, carrying only a subset of the original population's genetic diversity": "",
  "The founder effect occurs when a small number of individuals establish a new population, carrying only a fraction of the genetic diversity of the source population, which can lead to unusual allele frequencies.": "",
  "How does habitat fragmentation affect genetic diversity in wildlife populations?": "",
  "It has no effect on genetics": "",
  "It increases genetic diversity by creating new habitats": "",
  "It isolates populations, reducing gene flow and increasing inbreeding and genetic drift": "",
  "It always leads to immediate extinction": "",
  "Habitat fragmentation divides large populations into smaller, isolated groups. Without corridors for movement, gene flow decreases, and isolated subpopulations suffer from genetic drift and inbreeding.": "",
  "What role do mutations play in genetic diversity?": "",
  "Mutations are the ultimate source of all new genetic variation in a population": "",
  "Mutations only occur in laboratory settings": "",
  "Mutations always harm organisms": "",
  "Mutations decrease genetic diversity": "",
  "Mutations are random changes in DNA that create new alleles, serving as the ultimate source of genetic variation. While many mutations are neutral or harmful, some provide beneficial adaptations.": "",
  "What is a minimum viable population (MVP)?": "",
  "The number of individuals needed to start a zoo breeding program": "",
  "The smallest population size that can sustain itself and maintain genetic diversity over the long term": "",
  "The average population size of all species in an ecosystem": "",
  "The largest population an ecosystem can support": "",
  "The minimum viable population is the smallest number of individuals needed for a population to have a high probability of surviving over a specified time period, typically considering genetic diversity, demographic stochasticity, and environmental variation.": "",
  "Why are wildlife corridors important for maintaining genetic diversity?": "",
  "They prevent all disease transmission": "",
  "They allow individuals to move between fragmented habitats, maintaining gene flow between populations": "",
  "They provide shelter from predators": "",
  "They increase the amount of available food": "",
  "Wildlife corridors connect isolated habitat patches, enabling animals to move between them. This maintains gene flow, preventing the genetic isolation that leads to inbreeding depression and loss of diversity.": "",
  "What is genetic diversity?": "",
  "The number of different species in an ecosystem": "",
  "The variety of genes and alleles within a population or species": "",
  "The number of different ecosystems in a region": "",
  "The total number of organisms in a population": "",
  "Genetic diversity refers to the total variety of genes, alleles, and genotypes within a population or species. It is one of three levels of biodiversity (genetic, species, and ecosystem diversity).": "",
  "What does the term 'gene pool' mean?": "",
  "A body of water where genes are found": "",
  "A laboratory where genetic experiments are conducted": "",
  "The total collection of all genes and alleles present in a population": "",
  "The DNA of a single individual": "",
  "The gene pool is the complete set of unique alleles present in a population. A larger, more diverse gene pool provides more raw material for adaptation and evolution.": "",
  "What is 'allele frequency'?": "",
  "The proportion of a particular allele among all allele copies in a population": "",
  "The physical location of a gene on a chromosome": "",
  "The rate at which new mutations occur": "",
  "The number of chromosomes in an organism": "",
  "Allele frequency is the relative proportion of a particular allele at a specific gene locus in a population. Changes in allele frequencies over time indicate that evolution is occurring.": "",
  "What does 'gene flow' mean?": "",
  "The flow of water through an ecosystem": "",
  "The transfer of genetic material from one population to another through migration and interbreeding": "",
  "The expression of genes during development": "",
  "The replication of DNA during cell division": "",
  "Gene flow is the movement of alleles between populations through migration and subsequent interbreeding. It homogenizes allele frequencies between populations and introduces new genetic variation.": "",
  "What is meant by 'population bottleneck'?": "",
  "A drastic reduction in population size that causes a loss of genetic diversity": "",
  "When a population reaches carrying capacity": "",
  "The movement of individuals between populations": "",
  "When a population grows exponentially": "",
  "A population bottleneck is an event that drastically reduces population size, eliminating many alleles from the gene pool. The surviving population has much lower genetic diversity than the original.": "",
  "What does 'heterozygosity' refer to in population genetics?": "",
  "Having two different alleles at a gene locus, used as a measure of genetic diversity in populations": "",
  "Having two identical alleles at a gene locus": "",
  "The total number of genes in an organism": "",
  "The rate of reproduction in a population": "",
  "Heterozygosity refers to having two different alleles at a genetic locus. Population-level heterozygosity is a key measure of genetic diversity; higher heterozygosity generally indicates greater genetic health.": "",
  "What is 'natural selection'?": "",
  "Random changes in allele frequencies due to chance": "",
  "The process by which organisms with favorable traits are more likely to survive and reproduce, passing those traits to offspring": "",
  "The artificial breeding of organisms by humans": "",
  "Natural selection is the evolutionary mechanism where individuals with traits better suited to their environment have higher survival and reproductive success, causing beneficial alleles to increase in frequency.": "",
  "What does 'effective population size' mean?": "",
  "The total count of all individuals in a population": "",
  "The size of the largest population in an ecosystem": "",
  "The number of individuals in a population that actually contribute genes to the next generation": "",
  "The carrying capacity of the habitat": "",
  "Effective population size is often much smaller than the total census size because not all individuals breed equally. Factors like unequal sex ratios, variance in reproductive success, and population fluctuations reduce the effective size.": "",
  "What is 'genetic bottleneck'?": "",
  "The normal fluctuation of gene frequencies in large populations": "",
  "A method for measuring genetic diversity in a lab": "",
  "A sharp reduction in genetic variation caused by a dramatic decrease in population size": "",
  "A gradual increase in allele diversity over many generations": "",
  "A genetic bottleneck occurs when a population's size is drastically reduced, causing a random loss of alleles. The surviving population has reduced genetic variation regardless of which individuals happened to survive.": "",
  "What does 'adaptive potential' mean?": "",
  "A population's capacity to evolve and adapt to future environmental changes, which depends on its genetic diversity": "",
  "The current fitness of the best-adapted individual": "",
  "The speed at which organisms can move to new habitats": "",
  "The number of different species in an area": "",
  "Adaptive potential is the ability of a population to evolve in response to new environmental pressures. It depends directly on genetic diversity: more diverse populations have greater capacity to adapt.": "",
  "The Florida panther population declined to fewer than 30 individuals by the 1990s, and researchers documented kinked tails, heart defects, and low sperm quality. In 1995, eight female Texas pumas were introduced. Within a decade, genetic health improved dramatically. What conservation genetics concept does this illustrate?": "",
  "Genetic rescue through introducing individuals from a related population to restore gene flow and reduce inbreeding depression": "",
  "Genetic drift always benefits small populations": "",
  "Texas pumas replaced the Florida panthers entirely": "",
  "Inbreeding depression is beneficial for population health": "",
  "This is a landmark example of genetic rescue. Introducing Texas puma genes restored genetic diversity, reducing inbreeding depression and improving health, survival, and reproduction in the Florida panther population.": "",
  "A conservation group proposes building a wildlife corridor to connect two isolated forest fragments that each contain about 100 black bears. Opponents argue that the bears are fine in their current habitats. Using population genetics, how would you support the corridor proposal?": "",
  "Without gene flow, both small populations will lose genetic diversity through drift and inbreeding over generations, reducing their adaptive potential": "",
  "The corridor would only increase disease transmission": "",
  "Wildlife corridors only benefit bird species": "",
  "100 bears is always enough for long-term genetic health": "",
  "Two isolated populations of 100 bears each will independently lose genetic diversity over time. A corridor enabling even a few migrants per generation would maintain gene flow, preserving diversity and preventing inbreeding depression.": "",
  "After a devastating hurricane, a small island population of lizards is reduced from 10,000 to just 50 survivors. Genetic analysis shows the survivors happen to have an unusually high frequency of a rare allele for darker coloration. What two population genetics concepts explain this situation?": "",
  "Population bottleneck and genetic drift, which randomly altered allele frequencies in the small surviving population": "",
  "Mutation and immigration when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "Inbreeding and outbreeding within the broader context of population analysis": "",
  "Natural selection and gene flow when considering all relevant population factors": "",
  "The hurricane caused a population bottleneck (drastic population reduction). The unusual allele frequency in survivors is due to genetic drift (random sampling effect), not selection for darker coloration.": "",
  "A zoo breeding program for endangered California condors carefully tracks the pedigree of every individual to decide which birds should mate. Why is pedigree management so important in captive breeding?": "",
  "Pedigree tracking is unnecessary in captive breeding": "",
  "To ensure only the largest birds breed": "",
  "To select for specific feather colors": "",
  "To minimize inbreeding by pairing unrelated individuals, maintaining maximum genetic diversity in the captive population": "",
  "Pedigree management ensures that the most genetically unrelated individuals are paired, maximizing heterozygosity and preventing inbreeding depression, which is crucial for the long-term viability of the captive population.": "",
  "Researchers comparing two salmon populations find that one in a pristine river has high genetic diversity, while another in a dammed river has very low diversity despite similar population sizes. What explains the difference?": "",
  "Dams increase genetic diversity by creating new habitats": "",
  "The pristine river has more predators, which increases diversity": "",
  "Dams have no effect on fish genetics": "",
  "The dam blocks migration and gene flow, isolating the population and causing genetic diversity loss through drift and inbreeding": "",
  "Dams fragment river habitats and block the natural migration of salmon between breeding populations. Without gene flow from other groups, the isolated population loses diversity through drift and inbreeding.": "",
  "A plant species in an agricultural landscape exists only in small, scattered remnant patches of prairie. A geneticist finds that each patch has different dominant alleles and overall low heterozygosity. Which concept explains why each fragment is genetically distinct?": "",
  "High mutation rates in fragmented habitats": "",
  "The patches are too large for drift to matter": "",
  "Natural selection is driving different adaptations in each patch": "",
  "Genetic drift acting independently in each small, isolated population has randomly fixed different alleles": "",
  "In small, isolated populations, genetic drift has a strong effect, randomly changing allele frequencies. Different random outcomes in each fragment lead to different genetic compositions, while low heterozygosity results from drift and inbreeding.": "",
  "Climate change is causing warmer temperatures, and a tree species at its southern range limit is showing signs of heat stress. The northern edge of the range, however, shows healthy growth. A conservation geneticist proposes 'assisted gene flow' by planting seeds from heat-tolerant southern populations into central populations. What is the genetic rationale?": "",
  "Moving seeds never affects genetic diversity": "",
  "Southern trees are always genetically superior": "",
  "Central populations have too much genetic diversity already": "",
  "Introducing heat-adapted alleles from southern populations into central populations increases their adaptive potential to warming conditions": "",
  "Assisted gene flow introduces pre-adapted genetic variation from warm-adapted southern populations, providing central populations with alleles that may help them survive as conditions warm, boosting their adaptive potential.": "",
  "A critically endangered species has only 15 individuals remaining in the wild. A geneticist warns that even if the population grows to 500, it will still face long-term genetic problems. Why?": "",
  "Genetic diversity increases automatically as populations grow": "",
  "Populations of 500 are always genetically healthy": "",
  "The severe bottleneck of 15 individuals already eliminated most genetic variation, and population growth alone cannot recreate lost alleles": "",
  "Only mutations in the next generation matter": "",
  "Population growth increases numbers but not genetic diversity. The alleles lost during the bottleneck are gone permanently (unless reintroduced through gene flow). Recovery of genetic diversity through mutation alone takes thousands of generations.": "",
  "Agricultural scientists note that modern corn varieties, despite high yields, are genetically very uniform. A new fungal disease begins spreading rapidly through cornfields worldwide. How does the concept of genetic diversity explain this vulnerability?": "",
  "Genetically uniform crops are always resistant to disease": "",
  "Fungal diseases cannot affect crop plants": "",
  "Genetic diversity in crops is irrelevant to disease resistance": "",
  "Genetic uniformity means all plants have similar susceptibility, so a disease that can infect one plant can infect them all": "",
  "Genetic uniformity in monoculture crops means all plants share the same susceptibility. In a genetically diverse population, some individuals would likely carry resistance alleles, preventing total crop loss.": "",
  "Two populations of the same fish species live in lakes on opposite sides of a mountain. A road construction project creates a channel connecting the two lakes. After 20 years, genetic analysis shows the two populations have become more similar. Which evolutionary process has occurred?": "",
  "Identical mutations occurred in both populations simultaneously": "",
  "Gene flow through the connecting channel has homogenized allele frequencies between the populations": "",
  "Genetic drift made them more similar by chance": "",
  "Natural selection for similar traits": "",
  "The connecting channel enabled fish to move between lakes, creating gene flow. Over generations, migration and interbreeding homogenized allele frequencies, making the once-distinct populations genetically similar.": ""
}